      <bioghist id="aspace_c8a44fb22cd0b4fdda20b478fa28bca1">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>James Bell worked as a journalist and was a correspondent for Time, Inc. from 1942-1948. He served as White House correspondent from 1948-1950. Bell was bureau chief in the Middle East, 1951-1954; Central Europe, 1954-1956 and 1961-1966; China and Southeast Asia, 1956-1959; Africa, 1959-1961; New York, 1966-1968; Rome, 1968-1973; Atlanta, 1973-1976; and Boston, 1976-.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_147d6bb4af1dea543e2b29835b9266e0">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The papers consist of a typed manuscript, "The trials of Alger Hiss, as reported by James Bell, Time Incorporated," 734 pages in 2 volumes. The contents include trial I, June 1, 1949-July 8, 1949, and trial II, November 22, 1949-January 25, 1950.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
